}{}$\mathcal{T}$\end{document}</tex-math></inline-formula> has five subclones, where the root node subclone1 is comprised of normal cells only, and the other nodes are cancerous subclones caused by point mutations and/or CNAs on three loci A, B and C. The SNV and CNA genotypes of these subclones are shown in Figure <xref rid="f1" ref-type="fig">1</xref>B. The two SNVs occur at loci A and B give rise to subclone2. The loss of the mutant copy on locus B further generates subclone4 based on the genotype of subclone2. If one infers the tumor clone tree with only SNV data <inline-formula><tex-math notation="LaTeX" id="ImEquation11">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
