}{}$Z$\end{document}</tex-math></inline-formula>, one will most probably recover a linear evolutionary history as in Figure <xref rid="f1" ref-type="fig">1</xref>C. However, this is biased as it misses the identification of the two extra subclones (3 and 5), which respectively generated by a copy loss at locus A and a copy gain at locus C. Also, ignoring the CNA-driven loss of SNV at locus B in subclone4 may lead to misplacement of cells in subclone4 as the ancestor of cells in subclone2 and 5 on the SNV-based clone tree (Figure <xref rid="f1" ref-type="fig">1</xref>C). In such case, the full history can only be resolved by taking into account of information from both SNV (<inline-formula><tex-math notation="LaTeX" id="ImEquation12">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
